article:
The 'English football league system', also known as the 'football pyramid', is a
series of interconnected leagues for men's association football clubs in
England, with six teams from Wales and one from Guernsey also competing. The
system has a hierarchical format with promotion and relegation between leagues
at different levels, allowing even the smallest club the possibility of
ultimately rising to the very top of the system. There are more than 140
individual leagues, containing more than 480 divisions. The exact
number of clubs varies from year to year as clubs join and leave leagues or fold
altogether, but an estimated average of 15 clubs per division implies that more
than 7,000 teams of nearly 5,300 clubs are members of a league in the English
men's football league system.

The pyramid for Women's football in England is listed separately and runs to
nine tiers.

Not every English-based club plays in the English football league system; see
List of association football clubs playing in the league of another country.
